## Cron tasks

Scheduled tasks are **YAML files** in `../cron-tasks/`, run by the in-container scheduler ‚Äî there
are no systemd timers and no shell wrappers. To add one, write `../cron-tasks/<name>.yaml`:

```yaml
name: my-task                  # must match the filename
on_calendar: "Mon-Fri 09:00"   # when to run (systemd OnCalendar syntax)
model: claude-sonnet-4-6       # optional; omit for the default
prompt: |
  Plain-English instructions for the run. {{today}} substitution works.
  Use `broker call ...` for any service; post with ./bin/slack-tools.sh.
```

The scheduler picks it up on the next restart. See `../cron-tasks/_template.yaml` and the
examples beside it. Disable a task by deleting (or renaming) its file.

**Run a cron NOW (out of schedule):** you can't spawn the worker yourself (your shell has no
auth token by design) ‚Äî instead drop a trigger file and the scheduler runs it immediately,
exactly like a scheduled fire:

```bash
touch state/cron-triggers/<task-name>
```

The scheduler picks it up within ~5 seconds, refuses to double-fire a task that's already
running, and logs the run. So when the user says "run the prospecting cron now", that one
command is the whole job ‚Äî confirm it fired by checking the task's log a moment later.

